 High-Fidelity Prediction of Aeroshell Radiometric Sensor Contamination During Mars EDL

Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

This thesis develops a rigorously grounded mathematical framework and latency‚Äëconstrained modular architecture for predicting and correcting radiometric sensor contamination during Mars Entry, Descent, and Landing (EDL). The coupled thermochemical‚Äëoptical inverse problem is formulated in Sobolev and reproducing kernel Hilbert spaces, with well‚Äëposedness established via monotone operator theory and an Arbitrary Lagrangian‚ÄìEulerian (ALE) formulation that rigorously handles the moving ablation boundary. We replace heuristic convergence claims with statistically defensible guarantees: PAC‚ÄëBayesian generalization bounds for Physics‚ÄëInformed Neural Networks (PINNs) with collocation points treated as random uniform samples; Bayesian nonparametric credible sets for multi‚Äëfidelity Gaussian Process surrogates; explicit spectral truncation bounds for Machine‚ÄëLearned Interatomic Potentials (MLIPs) using smooth cutoff functions to ensure analyticity; and semismooth Newton convergence for M‚Äëestimation Kalman filtering with a complete proof of BD‚Äëregularity. System‚Äëlevel stability is proven constructively via incremental Input‚Äëto‚ÄëState Stability (ISS) using discrete‚Äëtime observability Gramians under a uniform observability condition, with explicit handling of state‚Äëdependent Kalman gains. The resulting architecture prioritizes differentiable physics kernels, distributionally robust estimators, and formal verification compatibility, providing a mathematically complete blueprint for future autonomous aerothermal instrumentation systems across planetary entry environments. Complete proofs of all main theorems are provided, and the theoretical convergence rates are validated through numerical experiments on synthetic Mars EDL trajectories.

