4.1 PAC‚ÄëBayesian Generalization for Hybrid Physics‚ÄëInformed Neural Networks

We consider a Physics‚ÄëInformed Neural Network (PINN) that approximates the temperature field $T(\mathbf{x},t)$ and the film thickness $\delta_{\text{film}}(t)$. The network parameters $\theta \in \mathbb{R}^W$ (weights and biases) define a function $u_\theta(\mathbf{x},t)$. The loss function combines data misfit, PDE residual, and radiative transfer equation (RTE) residual:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{PINN}}(\theta) = \underbrace{\frac{1}{N_d}\sum_{i=1}^{N_d} \|u_\theta(\mathbf{x}_i,t_i) - y_i\|^2}_{\mathcal{L}_{\text{data}}} 
+ \lambda_{\text{PDE}} \underbrace{\frac{1}{N_r}\sum_{j=1}^{N_r} \|\mathcal{R}_{\text{PDE}}[u_\theta](\mathbf{x}_j,t_j)\|^2}_{\mathcal{L}_{\text{PDE}}}
+ \mu_{\text{RTE}} \underbrace{\frac{1}{N_s}\sum_{k=1}^{N_s} \|\mathcal{R}_{\text{RTE}}[u_\theta](\mathbf{s}_k,\lambda_k)\|^2}_{\mathcal{L}_{\text{RTE}}},

where $\mathcal{R}_{\text{PDE}}[u] = \rho c_p (\partial_t u + \mathbf{w}\cdot\nabla u) - \nabla\cdot(k\nabla u) - \dot{q}_{\text{pyro}}(u) + \dot{q}_{\text{abl}}(u)$ is the heat equation residual (in ALE form), and $\mathcal{R}_{\text{RTE}}[u]$ is the residual of the non‚ÄëLTE radiative transfer equation discretized by the MRT‚ÄëLBM scheme.

Key assumption for probabilistic treatment: The collocation points $\{(\mathbf{x}_j,t_j)\}_{j=1}^{N_r}$ and $\{(\mathbf{s}_k,\lambda_k)\}_{k=1}^{N_s}$ are drawn independently from uniform distributions over $\Omega \times [0,T]$ and the line‚Äëof‚Äësight domain $\mathcal{S} \times [\lambda_1,\lambda_2]$, respectively. The data points $(\mathbf{x}_i,t_i,y_i)$ are i.i.d. from an unknown distribution $\mathcal{D}$.

Theorem 4.1 (PAC‚ÄëBayesian PINN Generalization Bound).
Let $\mathcal{H}$ be the class of neural networks with $L$ layers, $W$ parameters, and Lipschitz activation $\sigma$ satisfying $\operatorname{Lip}(\sigma) \le L_\sigma$. Let $Q$ be any data‚Äëdependent posterior distribution over weights and $P$ a fixed prior (e.g., Gaussian). Define the true risk

R_{\text{true}}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{(\mathbf{x},t,y)\sim \mathcal{D}}\bigl[\|u_\theta(\mathbf{x},t)-y\|^2\bigr] + \mathbb{E}_{(\mathbf{x},t)\sim \text{Unif}}\bigl[\|\mathcal{R}_{\text{PDE}}[u_\theta](\mathbf{x},t)\|^2\bigr] + \mathbb{E}_{(\mathbf{s},\lambda)\sim \text{Unif}}\bigl[\|\mathcal{R}_{\text{RTE}}[u_\theta](\mathbf{s},\lambda)\|^2\bigr].

Assume the true solution satisfies $T^* \in H^k(\Omega)$ with $k > d/2$ ($d=3$). Let $\epsilon_{\text{MRT}} = O(\Delta x^2 + \Delta t^2)$ be the truncation bias of the MRT‚ÄëLBM scheme. Then with probability at least $1-\delta$ over the joint draw of training data $S_d$ (size $N_d$), PDE collocation points $S_r$ (size $N_r$), and RTE collocation points $S_s$ (size $N_s$),

\mathbb{E}_{\theta \sim Q}\bigl[R_{\text{true}}(\theta)\bigr] 
\le \mathbb{E}_{\theta \sim Q}\bigl[\mathcal{L}_{\text{PINN}}(\theta)\bigr] 
+ \sqrt{\frac{\operatorname{KL}(Q\|P) + \ln(2\sqrt{N_d}/\delta)}{2N_d}}
+ C_1 \frac{\|T^*\|_{H^k}}{N_r^{1/d}} 
+ C_2 \frac{\|I^*\|_{H^1}}{N_s^{1/2}} 
+ \epsilon_{\text{MRT}}^2,

where $C_1, C_2$ are constants depending on the domain and the PDE coefficients, and $\operatorname{KL}(Q\|P)$ is the Kullback‚ÄìLeibler divergence.

Proof. The proof is structured in four parts.

Part 1: PAC‚ÄëBayes inequality for the data term.
Apply McAllester‚Äôs PAC‚ÄëBayes theorem (sharpened by Catoni, 2007) to the data loss $\ell_{\text{data}}(\theta; (\mathbf{x},t,y)) = \|u_\theta(\mathbf{x},t)-y\|^2$, which is bounded by $B$ (since $u_\theta$ and $y$ are bounded in practice). For any $\delta \in (0,1)$, with probability $\ge 1-\delta$ over $S_d$,

\mathbb{E}_{\theta\sim Q}[R_{\text{data}}(\theta)] \le \mathbb{E}_{\theta\sim Q}[\hat{R}_{\text{data}}(\theta)] + \sqrt{\frac{\operatorname{KL}(Q\|P) + \ln(2\sqrt{N_d}/\delta)}{2N_d}},

where $R_{\text{data}}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{(\mathbf{x},t,y)\sim\mathcal{D}}[\ell_{\text{data}}]$ and $\hat{R}_{\text{data}}(\theta) = \frac{1}{N_d}\sum_{i=1}^{N_d} \ell_{\text{data}}(\theta; \mathbf{z}_i)$.

Part 2: Bias of the empirical PDE residual.
The true PDE risk is $\mathbb{E}_{(\mathbf{x},t)\sim\text{Unif}}[\|\mathcal{R}_{\text{PDE}}[u_\theta](\mathbf{x},t)\|^2]$. The empirical estimate uses $N_r$ uniform collocation points. For a fixed $\theta$, the function $f(\mathbf{x},t) = \|\mathcal{R}_{\text{PDE}}[u_\theta](\mathbf{x},t)\|^2$ is Lipschitz in $(\mathbf{x},t)$ because $u_\theta$ is smooth (neural network with Lipschitz activations) and the PDE coefficients are Lipschitz. By the quasi‚ÄëMonte Carlo error bound for Lipschitz functions (Dick & Pillichshammer, 2010, Theorem 3.5), using a Sobol sequence or random uniform points,

\bigl|\mathbb{E}_{\text{Unif}}[f] - \hat{f}_{N_r}\bigr| \le C_f \, \text{Disc}^*(\{(\mathbf{x}_j,t_j)\}) \le \frac{C \operatorname{Lip}(f)}{N_r^{1/d}}.

However, this holds for each $\theta$. To obtain a uniform bound over $\theta$ in the support of $Q$, we note that the function class $\mathcal{F} = \{ (\mathbf{x},t) \mapsto \|\mathcal{R}_{\text{PDE}}[u_\theta](\mathbf{x},t)\|^2 : \theta \in \operatorname{supp}(Q) \}$ has a covering number that grows polynomially in $W$ and $L$. Using a standard chaining argument (van der Vaart & Wellner, 1996), we obtain

\sup_{\theta \in \operatorname{supp}(Q)} \bigl|\mathbb{E}[f_\theta] - \hat{f}_{\theta,N_r}\bigr| \le C_1 \frac{\|T^*\|_{H^k}}{N_r^{1/d}} \quad \text{with high probability},

where the dependence on $\|T^*\|_{H^k}$ enters because the PDE residual involves derivatives of $u_\theta$, and the true solution provides a baseline regularity.

Part 3: Bias of the empirical RTE residual.
The MRT‚ÄëLBM scheme is a second‚Äëorder accurate discretization of the non‚ÄëLTE radiative transfer equation. For any sufficiently smooth intensity $I_\lambda$, the numerical solution $I_\lambda^{\text{MRT}}$ satisfies

\|\mathcal{R}_{\text{RTE}}[u_\theta] - \mathcal{R}_{\text{RTE}}^{\text{exact}}[u_\theta]\|_{L^2} \le \epsilon_{\text{MRT}} = C_{\text{MRT}}(\Delta x^2 + \Delta t^2),

where $\Delta x$ is the lattice spacing and $\Delta t$ the time step. The empirical RTE loss $\mathcal{L}_{\text{RTE}}$ uses $N_s$ random rays and wavelengths. By the same quasi‚ÄëMonte Carlo argument (now with $d=2$: ray coordinate $s$ and wavelength $\lambda$), the Monte Carlo integration error is bounded by $C_2 N_s^{-1/2}$ times the $H^1$ norm of the squared residual. Since the true intensity $I^*$ belongs to $H^1$ (from the Sobolev regularity of the RTE solution), we get the term $C_2 \|I^*\|_{H^1} / \sqrt{N_s}$.

Part 4: Combining the bounds.
The total true risk is the sum of the three expectations. The empirical PINN loss is $\mathcal{L}_{\text{PINN}}(\theta) = \hat{R}_{\text{data}}(\theta) + \lambda_{\text{PDE}} \hat{R}_{\text{PDE}}(\theta) + \mu_{\text{RTE}} \hat{R}_{\text{RTE}}(\theta)$. By linearity of expectation over $Q$, we have

\mathbb{E}_Q[R_{\text{true}}] \le \mathbb{E}_Q[\hat{R}_{\text{data}}] + \mathbb{E}_Q[\hat{R}_{\text{PDE}}] + \mathbb{E}_Q[\hat{R}_{\text{RTE}}] + \text{error terms}.

Plugging the bounds from Parts 1‚Äì3 and absorbing constants into $C_1$, $C_2$ yields the theorem. The term $\epsilon_{\text{MRT}}^2$ appears because the empirical RTE loss measures the residual of the discrete scheme, not the exact residual; the difference between true and discrete residuals is bounded by $\epsilon_{\text{MRT}}$. ‚àé

Remark 4.1. The bound is dimension‚Äëdependent via $N_r^{-1/d}$, which in 3D gives $N_r^{-1/3}$. This is typical for quasi‚ÄëMonte Carlo integration of Lipschitz functions. To improve the rate, one can use higher‚Äëorder quasi‚ÄëMonte Carlo or adaptive sampling.

