CHAPTER 5: SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE & IMPLEMENTATION DESIGN

5.1 Modular Computational Architecture

The system is partitioned into three tiers (see Figure 5.1 for a schematic):

Tier 1: Offline Training (ground‚Äëbased, prior to EDL)

¬∑ Generate SNAP potentials from DFT data; certify using Lemma 4.3 (choose $J_{\max}$ to achieve desired $\epsilon_{\text{trunc}}$).
¬∑ Train multi‚Äëfidelity GP: run low‚Äëfidelity CFD ($N_l = 10^4$) and high‚Äëfidelity CFD ($N_h = 200$); optimize kernel hyperparameters via ELBO maximization (Theorem 4.2).
¬∑ Train PINN prior: use synthetic data from the GP surrogate; calibrate capacity via PAC‚ÄëBayesian bound (choose network size $W$ such that $\operatorname{KL}(Q\|P)$ is below a threshold).
¬∑ All outputs are stored as model files (weights, hyperparameters, inducing points) and loaded onto the onboard computer.

Tier 2: Onboard Inference (during EDL, $<10$ ms per cycle)

¬∑ State estimator: PCE‚ÄëMIEKF (Polynomial Chaos Expansion for uncertainty propagation, combined with M‚Äëestimation). The dynamics are propagated using a reduced‚Äëorder model (ROM) of the TPS. The measurement update uses the MIEKF with semismooth Newton (Theorem 4.4).
