CHAPTER 6: THEORETICAL SYNTHESIS & COMPOSITION

6.1 End‚Äëto‚ÄëEnd Error Propagation

The total prediction error $\epsilon_{\text{total}}$ for the radiometric signal $I_{\text{meas}}$ arises from four sources: MLIP truncation, GP approximation, PINN generalization, and MIEKF estimation error. We assume these errors are independent (a conservative bound) and combine them in a sum‚Äëof‚Äësquares fashion.

Theorem 6.1 (Error composition).
Let $\epsilon_{\text{MLIP}} = \max_{i,j} |B_{J_1,J_2,J} - B_{J_1,J_2,J}^{(J_{\max})}|$ be bounded by Lemma 4.3. Let $\epsilon_{\text{GP}} = \sup_{\mathbf{x}} \sigma_{\text{post}}(\mathbf{x})$ be bounded by Theorem 4.2. Let $\epsilon_{\text{PINN}} = \sqrt{\mathbb{E}_{\theta\sim Q}[R_{\text{true}}(\theta)]}$ be bounded by Theorem 4.1. Let $\epsilon_{\text{MIEKF}} = \sup_k \|e_k\|$ be bounded by the ISS gain (Theorem 5.1). Then the mean‚Äësquared error of the predicted radiometric signal satisfies

\mathbb{E}[\epsilon_{\text{total}}^2] \le C_1 \epsilon_{\text{MLIP}}^2 + C_2 \epsilon_{\text{GP}}^2 + C_3 \epsilon_{\text{PINN}}^2 + C_4 \epsilon_{\text{MIEKF}}^2,

where $C_1, C_2, C_3, C_4$ are sensitivity coefficients (the Lipschitz constants of the mapping from each component to the final output). Moreover, as the computational budgets increase ($J_{\max} \to \infty$, $m \to \infty$, $N_d, N_r, N_s \to \infty$), each $\epsilon$ tends to zero, hence $\epsilon_{\text{total}} \to 0$ in mean square.

Proof. The radiometric signal $I_{\text{meas}}$ is a function $I_{\text{meas}} = \Phi(T, \delta_{\text{film}}, \kappa_\lambda, q_{\text{rad}})$. The MLIP affects the simulation of $T$ and $\delta_{\text{film}}$ via the material properties; the GP provides a surrogate for the forward map; the PINN approximates the inverse; the MIEKF filters the measurements. The composition is Lipschitz (since all maps are Lipschitz on bounded domains). The total error is bounded by the sum of Lipschitz constants times individual errors. The independence assumption leads to the sum of squares. ‚àé

6.2 Cross‚ÄëPlanetary Extensibility

The architecture is parameter‚Äëagnostic. For a mission to Venus or Titan, only the following need to be replaced:

¬∑ Sticking coefficient $\gamma(T, \theta)$: new functional form from experimental data (e.g., for sulfuric acid droplets on Venus).
¬∑ Spectral absorption $\kappa_\lambda^{\text{gas}}$: update to the relevant atmospheric composition (CO‚ÇÇ for Venus, CH‚ÇÑ for Titan).
¬∑ Non‚ÄëLTE rate coefficients $k_{ij}$: new vibrational excitation rates.
¬∑ Prior distributions and kernel hyperparameters: recalibrated via offline training on mission‚Äëspecific CFD.

All theorems (well‚Äëposedness, identifiability, convergence, stability) hold because they rely only on structural properties: Lipschitz continuity of coefficients, monotonicity of pyrolysis, compactness of the forward operator, and uniform observability (which is a property of the sensor geometry and entry trajectory, not the specific material). Thus the framework is mathematically portable.

6.3 Future Design Pathways

1. Differentiable Physics Registry: Implement all forward operators (ALE heat equation, RTE, deposition ODE) as differentiable modules in JAX or PyTorch. This enables gradient‚Äëbased architecture search and online tuning of hyperparameters (e.g., $\lambda$, $\mu$ in the PINN loss) using Bayesian optimization.
2. Distributionally Robust Optimization: Replace the Huber loss with a Wasserstein distributionally robust filter to handle heavy‚Äëtailed outliers during dust storms. The M‚Äëestimator becomes a minimax problem; the semismooth Newton analysis extends because the influence function remains piecewise linear.
3. Neural SMT Verification: Integrate the PINN with Satisfiability Modulo Theories (SMT) solvers. Encode the neural network as a piecewise linear function (for ReLU activations) and use dReal or Marabou to check safety properties (e.g., $\|u_\theta(\mathbf{x},t) - T_{\text{safe}}\| \le \epsilon$ for all $\mathbf{x},t$ in a reachable set). This provides formal guarantees on the neural network‚Äôs output.
4. Online Model Adaptation: Use the PAC‚ÄëBayesian bound as a regularizer to adapt the PINN weights during EDL when new data arrives. The KL divergence can be updated incrementally using variational inference.

