7.2 Limitations and Open Problems

Despite the theoretical depth, several limitations must be acknowledged.

L1 ‚Äì Uniform observability assumption. Theorem 5.1 requires $\mathcal{O}_k \succeq \alpha I$ uniformly in $k$. For Mars EDL, this holds along nominal trajectories, but off-nominal tumbling or sensor failures could violate it. A remedy is to use a time-varying observability metric and a switching Lyapunov function (Hespanha & Morse, 1999).

L2 ‚Äì Independence of error sources. Theorem 6.1 assumes independence of $\epsilon_{\text{MLIP}}$, $\epsilon_{\text{GP}}$, $\epsilon_{\text{PINN}}$, $\epsilon_{\text{MIEKF}}$. In reality, correlations exist (e.g., GP and PINN share training data). A sharper bound using Fr√©chet derivatives and Cauchy‚ÄìSchwarz gives

\mathbb{E}[\epsilon_{\text{total}}^2] \le \left( \sum_{i=1}^4 \sqrt{C_i} \, \mathbb{E}[\epsilon_i^2]^{1/2} \right)^2,

which is still valid but less conservative.

L3 ‚Äì Smooth cutoff implementation. Lemma 4.3 assumes a $C^\infty$ cutoff function, while many SNAP implementations use a polynomial cutoff that is only $C^k$ for finite $k$. The exponential decay becomes algebraic in practice, but with a large exponent. We recommend the cosine taper $\varphi(r) = \frac12(1+\cos(\pi r/R_c))$ for $r\le R_c$, which is $C^1$ but not $C^\infty$; however, its analytic continuation has a finite radius, leading to exponential decay up to a pre-factor.

L4 ‚Äì Real-time KL monitoring. Computing $\operatorname{KL}(Q\|P)$ for a deep neural network online is expensive. We propose using a variational approximation $Q(\theta) \approx \mathcal{N}(\mu, \operatorname{diag}(\sigma^2))$ and updating the KL term via the closed-form expression

\operatorname{KL}(Q\|P) = \frac12 \sum_{i=1}^W \left( \frac{\mu_i^2}{\sigma_{P,i}^2} + \frac{\sigma_{Q,i}^2}{\sigma_{P,i}^2} - 1 - \log\frac{\sigma_{Q,i}^2}{\sigma_{P,i}^2} \right),

which costs $O(W)$ per cycle.

Open problems for future research.

1. Distributionally robust EDL estimation. Replace the Huber loss with a Wasserstein distributionally robust filter. The semismooth Newton analysis extends because the influence function remains piecewise linear; however, the Kalman gain becomes state-dependent in a more complex way, and the ISS proof requires a new contraction argument.
2. Neural SMT verification. Encode the trained PINN as a piecewise linear function (using ReLU activations) and use SMT solvers (e.g., dReal, Marabou) to verify safety properties over the reachable set. This would provide formal guarantees on the neural network‚Äôs output, complementing the PAC-Bayesian probabilistic bounds.
3. Online model adaptation. Use the PAC-Bayesian bound as a regularizer to adapt the PINN weights during EDL when new data arrives. Variational online learning algorithms (e.g., stochastic variational inference) can maintain the KL divergence below the safety threshold $\tau_{\text{KL}}$.
4. Differentiable physics registry. Implement all forward operators (ALE heat equation, RTE, deposition ODE) as differentiable modules in JAX or PyTorch. This would enable end-to-end gradient-based optimization of the entire pipeline, from sensor placement to estimator gains.
5. Experimental validation. The theoretical convergence rates should be validated on arc-jet test data or actual EDL telemetry from past Mars missions (e.g., MSL, Mars 2020). This requires a dedicated data-sharing agreement with NASA/JPL.

7.3 Final Remarks

The exploration of Mars has entered a new era, with increasingly ambitious missions demanding higher levels of autonomy. The ability to predict‚Äîand correct for‚Äîradiometric sensor contamination in real time is not a luxury but a necessity for safe precision landing. This dissertation has provided the mathematical foundations for such capability: not heuristics, but theorems; not ad-hoc convergence claims, but statistically guaranteed bounds; not black-box components, but a modular architecture with formal stability proofs.

The framework developed here is parameter-agnostic and extensible to other planetary bodies. For Venus, replace the sticking coefficient with that of sulfuric acid; for Titan, update the spectral absorption to methane; for Europa, adjust the non-LTE rate coefficients. The mathematics remains unchanged.

As we look toward human missions to Mars, the need for certifiable, explainable, and robust autonomy becomes even more acute. This work is a step in that direction‚Äîa blueprint for future autonomous aerothermal instrumentation systems. The sensors may contaminate, but the mathematics will hold.

