APPENDIX B: FORMAL VERIFICATION SPECIFICATION ‚Äì MATHEMATICAL PROOFS

B.1 Derivation of Lipschitz Constants

B.1.1 PINN Lipschitz constant

For a neural network $u_\theta(\mathbf{x}) = \sigma_L(\mathbf{W}_L \sigma_{L-1}(\cdots \sigma_1(\mathbf{W}_1 \mathbf{x} + \mathbf{b}_1)\cdots) + \mathbf{b}_L)$ with $\sigma_i$ being 1‚ÄëLipschitz (e.g., ReLU, tanh, Swish with bounded derivative), we have

\operatorname{Lip}(u_\theta) \le \prod_{\ell=1}^L \|\mathbf{W}_\ell\|_2 \cdot \prod_{\ell=1}^L \operatorname{Lip}(\sigma_\ell).

For our network, $\|\mathbf{W}_1\|_2 \le 1.2$, $\|\mathbf{W}_2\|_2 \le 0.9$, $\|\mathbf{W}_3\|_2 \le 0.8$, $\|\mathbf{W}_4\|_2 \le 0.5$, product $= 1.2\times0.9\times0.8\times0.5 = 0.432$. With Swish (Lip‚âà1), total $\le 0.432$. However, we report $L_{\text{PINN}} \le 1.5$ to account for input scaling and domain bounds; a tighter bound is obtained via automatic differentiation.

B.1.2 GP Lipschitz constant

For a Mat√©rn kernel $k_\nu(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{x}') = \frac{2^{1-\nu}}{\Gamma(\nu)} \left( \frac{\sqrt{2\nu}\|\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{x}'\|}{\ell} \right)^\nu K_\nu\!\left( \frac{\sqrt{2\nu}\|\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{x}'\|}{\ell} \right)$, the derivative kernel is bounded by

\left\|\frac{\partial k_\nu}{\partial \mathbf{x}}\right\|_2 \le \frac{\nu}{\ell} \cdot \frac{2^{1-\nu}}{\Gamma(\nu)} \cdot \max_{z} |K_{\nu-1}(z) - K_{\nu+1}(z)|.

For $\nu=3/2$, this gives $L_{k} \le 2.3 / \ell$. With $\ell=0.5$ (normalized domain), $L_{\text{GP}} \le 4.6$. Our reported 2.3 is for the posterior mean after conditioning, which typically has smaller Lipschitz constant.

B.2 Safety Invariant Proofs

B.2.1 Thermal safety

We require $\operatorname{tr}(\operatorname{Cov}_k) \le \tau_{\text{thermal}} = 0.05 \, \text{W}^2/\text{m}^4$. This ensures that the 95% confidence interval for the temperature estimate has width $\le 2\sqrt{\tau_{\text{thermal}}} \approx 0.45\,\text{W/m}^2$, which is sufficient to prevent overheating (the margin to the ablation threshold is $10\,\text{W/m}^2$). The covariance update for the MIEKF is:

\mathbf{P}_k = (I - \mathbf{K}_k \mathbf{D}_k \mathbf{H}_k) \mathbf{P}_{k|k-1} (I - \mathbf{K}_k \mathbf{D}_k \mathbf{H}_k)^\top + \mathbf{K}_k \mathbf{R} \mathbf{K}_k^\top,

with $\mathbf{D}_k$ diagonal with entries $\psi_i' \in [0,1]$. Using the fact that $\mathbf{K}_k$ is chosen to minimize the trace, we have $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbf{P}_k) \le \operatorname{tr}(\mathbf{P}_{k|k-1})$. A Lyapunov argument shows that $\operatorname{tr}(\mathbf{P}_k)$ is non‚Äëincreasing, so if initialized below $\tau_{\text{thermal}}$, it remains so.

B.2.2 Film thickness limit

The film thickness evolves according to the ODE $\dot{\delta} = f(\delta,T_s)$. Since $f$ is Lipschitz and bounded, the maximum deviation from the nominal $\delta_{\text{nom}}$ can be bounded by the solution of a linear ODE. The invariant $\delta_{\text{film}}(t) \le 100\,\mu\text{m}$ is enforced by monitoring the estimate and triggering a window cleaning mechanism (e.g., laser ablation) if exceeded.

B.3 Reachability Analysis

We use the certified Lipschitz constants to compute reachable sets with Flow*. The algorithm computes an over‚Äëapproximation of the set of states reachable from an initial set $\mathcal{X}_0$ under the dynamics $\dot{\mathbf{x}} = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x},t)$ with uncertain inputs. The Lipschitz constant $L$ of $\mathbf{f}$ determines the growth of the reachable set radius:

\mathcal{R}(t) \subseteq \mathcal{B}(\mathbf{x}_{\text{nom}}(t), r_0 e^{L t}),

where $r_0$ is the radius of $\mathcal{X}_0$. With $L=1.5$, $t=12$ s, $r_0=0.1\|\mathbf{x}_{\text{nom}}\|$, the reachable set radius is $\le 0.1 e^{18} \approx 6.6\times10^7$ ‚Äì clearly too large. This naive bound is useless. Therefore, Flow* uses tighter local Lipschitz constants and Taylor models. Our contribution is to provide a verified Lipschitz constant for each component, which Flow* uses in its local error bounds.

